h3.The issue
Assuming you have a group on your instance such as "Bug Killer Group", and you wish to create a space for this group to work on. You decide then to create this space via REST, since one of your colleagues already have a script ready and it will allow you to create the space and assign permissions with ease. 

h3.Steps to Replicate
Following the [REST API Documentation|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/#api-space-post], you execute the following command on your terminal:
{code}
curl --request POST \
  --user myUser@myDomain.com \
  --header 'Accept: application/json' \
  --header 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  --data '
  {
    "key": "BGK",
    "description": {
      "plain": { "value": "string", "representation": "string" }
    },
    "name": "Bug Killer Space",
    "permissions": [
      {
        "unlicensedAccess": "false",
        "operation": { "targetType": "space", "operation": "read" },

        "anonymousAccess": "false",
        "subjects": {
          "_expandable": { "user": "" },

          "group": {
            "results": [
              { "name": "Bug Killer Group", "type": "group" }
            ],
            "size": 1
          }
        }
      }]}' \
  --url 'https://myinstance.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/space'
{code}

h3.The error
Then, you receive a 200 Status, everything seems in order. You go to your Space Directory, and there lays the created space. Once you enter the "Space Permissions" page you were expecting it to be in order as well. Instead, you face the following error message under the newly created permission:
!Screen Shot 2018-03-28 at 10.43.57.png|thumbnail! 

h3.Expected behavior
The Case would not be a problem since it was also specified in the request itself.
